\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1 139. PyCharm's Charming Features (while you wait for the download to finish)\par

\pard{\pntext\f2\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf2\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\fi-360\li720\sa200\sl276\slmult1\ulnone\fs24 At this point, we've been using Replit as our text editor\ul\fs28\par
{\pntext\f2\'B7\tab}\ulnone\fs24 Replit has great features like:\ul\fs28\par

\pard{\pntext\f2\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf2\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\fi-360\li1080\sa200\sl276\slmult1\ulnone\fs24 Forking your code, sharing code, no setup or installations necessary\ul\fs28\par

\pard{\pntext\f2\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf2\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\fi-360\li720\sa200\sl276\slmult1\ulnone\fs24 However, when we move into bigger and more advanced projects, Replit may inevitably run into limitations. These contraints are things we want to avoid\ul\fs28\par
{\pntext\f2\'B7\tab}\ulnone\fs24 With PyCharm, we don't need to worry about these limitations.\ul\fs28\par
{\pntext\f2\'B7\tab}\ulnone\fs24 Here's a few of PyCharm features that willl help us program:\ul\fs28\par

\pard{\pntext\f2\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf2\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\fi-360\li1080\sa200\sl276\slmult1\fs24 Spell Check\ulnone  - PyCharm will point out any words that need to be corrected\ul\fs28\par
{\pntext\f2\'B7\tab}\fs24 More Space\ulnone  - You can split two separate files into separate windows. Writing code will be easier as you can view 2 files at once and not bounce back and forth between them\ul\fs28\par
{\pntext\f2\'B7\tab}\fs24 Built-In Linter\ulnone  - This system checks your code and makes sure that it's in accordance to Python's style guide PEP 8: {{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK https://peps.python.org/pep-0008/ }}{\fldrslt{https://peps.python.org/pep-0008/\ul0\cf0}}}}\ul\f0\fs28\par

\pard{\pntext\f2\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf2\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\fi-360\li1440\sa200\sl276\slmult1\ulnone\fs24 If there are non-program breaking issues, PyCharm will let you know to abide by the style guide (whitespace before and after newly declared functions, proper indentation, etc.)\ul\fs28\par
{\pntext\f2\'B7\tab}\ulnone\fs24 PyCharm will tell you what you need to do to abide by these rules by hovering over the affected lines \ul\fs28\par

\pard{\pntext\f2\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf2\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\fi-360\li1080\sa200\sl276\slmult1\fs24 Local History\ulnone  - You can view all of your coding history. PyCharm will place a "before" and "after" version of the file you created side by side and show you what you've changed.\ul\fs28\par

\pard{\pntext\f2\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf2\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\fi-360\li1440\sa200\sl276\slmult1\ulnone\fs24 You can also revert back to earlier changes if need be\ul\fs28\par
{\pntext\f2\'B7\tab}\ulnone\fs24 You can find this option under Version control - Local History \ul\fs28\par

\pard{\pntext\f2\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf2\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\fi-360\li1080\sa200\sl276\slmult1\fs24 View Structure\ulnone  - PyCharm can list out all of data structures and variables that you use in the \b Structure \b0 tab on the left indicated by 3 blocks\ul\fs28\par

\pard{\pntext\f2\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf2\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\fi-360\li1440\sa200\sl276\slmult1\ulnone\fs24 Clicking on the variable, data structure, etc. will bring you to that item in particular in your code\ul\fs28\par
{\pntext\f2\'B7\tab}\ulnone\fs24 This becomes exceptionally helpful the larger your programs become\ul\fs28\par

\pard{\pntext\f2\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf2\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\fi-360\li1080\sa200\sl276\slmult1\fs24 Refactor Rename\ulnone  - You can rename multiple data structures at once instead of renaming that singular data structure once at a time. \ul\fs28\par

